Sustainable and Humane Agriculture? Can we Afford It?

Spurred by animal rights and climate activists, the American agricultural system is under review. Radical change to agricultural production is demanded, yet is it currently possible?

By

Heather Haddon

April 24, 2020 9:02 am ET
  • Save
  • Share
  • Text
  • 367

Increasingly, consumers are not only taking interest in the impact of food on their bodies but also on the world around them. You see it manifest on food packaging all up and down the grocery aisles. Happy cows grazing on plush fields line the dairy section. Bright colors and big labels tout high-protein and little sugar. Boxes, bags, and bottles emboldened with buzzwords: organic, vegan, cage-free, locally grown, eco-friendly, you know the mix. Discount labels are things of the past, health is in.

Currently, I live on and help operate a small farm in central New Jersey. As if Old Mac lived here himself, cows, chicken, pigs, and turkeys are all raised on the property. The cows graze on acres of land with plenty of sweet feed in their troughs and the chickens roam their coup under the protective watch of two vengeful guard dogs. However, this is not the norm. Commercial farms operate on a scale hundreds of times larger than this one. Farming is expensive; you either buy more land or use what you got more efficiently. For commercial farms, this often means resorting to factory farming. Dense packed halls of livestock eating from mechanized feeding troughs. High efficiency, high environmental cost, but most importantly high returns. No sentient being should live like this, but can we afford the change?

Revolutionary change to the means by which we produce food is desperately needed, yet too often do its supporters ignore the basic obstacles slowing its implementation. The change is needed but not everyone can afford it yet. If we don’t stop and think we risk leaving some groups behind. Currently, the socio-economic implications of achieving sustainability and humane agriculture have not received proper attention at the disproportionate expense of poorer and minority Americans.

Despite the good intentions of animal rights and climate activists, access in the United States to food is unjust and inequitable. If we continue too quickly, we’ll risk the prized healthy, sustainable, and humanely raised foods becoming exclusive to wealthier American communities and limit the true environmental benefits of sustainable agriculture. It is vital that in this mission to restructure the food system that the access to sustainable and humanely grown food is extended to underprivileged populations.

Food documentaries, such as Food, Inc, are widely known to have “lifted the veil” on the horrors of America’s industrial food production system and the government policies that keep them afloat. They operate with the understanding that education is what will solve the system’s issues. That a lack of education is the constraint that holds back consumers from purchasing sustainably produced foods. However, this approach misses a large portion of the American population: those with no choice over what they eat.

According to the University California Davis center for poverty, an estimated 40 million Americans live in poverty. Additionally, 15 million households were considered food-insecure. These Americans are disproportionately minorities and live in urban communities. For decades, low-income communities have suffered a profound lack of access to healthy and fresh food. In hundreds of neighborhoods across the United States, nutritious, high quality, and affordable food is out of reach. Inequitable access to healthy food is a major contributor leading to higher rates of health complications, such as heart disease and diabetes, in poorer communities. Instead of grocery stores and farmer’s markets, poor communities find themselves stuck in so-called “Food deserts”, laden with convenience stores and fast food restaurants selling cheap unhealthy processed foods.

Many advocate that poor communities should take it upon themselves to produce their own fresh produce within their communities. While community gardens could function as an important tool for developing community pride, they are often not feasible in urban communities. High capital costs and low volume of suitable growing locations lead to incredibly expensive costs for residents that are easily priced out by wealthier investors. Furthermore, high water requirements and low soil quality also add to the list obstacles facing garden proponents. Most of all, it should not be the responsibility of poorer communities to take the production of basic needs, healthy produce, into their own hands when the production of produce is in no short supply in the United States.
